1) What are the different editions of Java?
-->The four main editions of Java, designed for specific development needs, are Java SE (Standard Edition), 
    Java EE (Enterprise Edition), Java ME (Micro Edition), and JavaFX. They cover everything from basic desktop applications 
    and complex, large-scale enterprise server systems to mobile, embedded devices, and rich internet applications.

2) What is Java SE used for?
-->Java Platform, Standard Edition (Oracle) (Java SE) is the foundational platform for developing and deploying 
    general-purpose applications across various environments, including desktops, servers, and cloud environments. 

3) What is Java EE (Jakarta EE), and what does it include?
-->Jakarta EE (formerly Java EE) is a set of specifications, APIs, and runtime environments built on Java SE for creating enterprise-grade, cloud-native, and server-side applications. 

4) What is Java ME used for?
-->Java ME (Micro Edition) is a computing platform for developing and deploying applications on mobile and embedded devices with limited resources, such as memory and processing power.


5) What is JavaFX, and when is it used?
-->JavaFX is a modern, open-source Java library (often called OpenJFX) used to create rich graphical user interfaces (GUIs) and desktop applications

6) What is the difference between Java SE and Java EE?
-->Java SE (Standard Edition) is the core Java platform for developing desktop and general-purpose applications, while Java EE (Enterprise Edition - now Jakarta EE) 
    is built on top of SE to provide APIs and a runtime environment for large-scale, multi-tiered, and secure network applications.

7) Can you build web applications with Java SE?
-->Yes, it is possible to build web applications using Java SE, but it typically requires additional libraries, a web server (like Apache Tomcat or Jetty),
    or a web framework, as Java SE itself is primarily for standalone applications. 

